1
00:00:00,560 --> 00:00:05,120
I don’t know about you, but I don’t like 
spending all day in front of my trading screen.  

2
00:00:05,120 --> 00:00:09,600
I want to have the time to do other activities I 
enjoy, while having some trades in the background. 

3
00:00:10,160 --> 00:00:15,360
So, I’m revealing a profitable one-hour trading 
strategy and I will share how I find leading  

4
00:00:15,360 --> 00:00:20,640
signals, how I know right at the beginning of 
the day if the market is worth trading or not,  

5
00:00:20,640 --> 00:00:23,600
and all of this by spending 
just 30 minutes in the morning. 

6
00:00:24,160 --> 00:00:28,000
Before we begin, if you want to show your 
support, please leave a like to help us  

7
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:32,240
with Youtube algorithm and turn on the bell, so 
you don’t miss when new videos are released.
  

8
00:00:33,680 --> 00:00:39,120
The speed of the markets on lower time frames 
represents a big problem for many traders.  

9
00:00:39,120 --> 00:00:42,960
All the trading decisions you make 
will have to be done much faster. 

10
00:00:42,960 --> 00:00:46,640
One solution to this problem is 
trading the one hour time frame. 

11
00:00:47,440 --> 00:00:52,080
The 1 hour chart offers flexibility, 
there’s considerably less noise  

12
00:00:52,080 --> 00:00:57,200
and it also generates enough trades so you 
have lots of decent chances of making money. 

13
00:00:57,200 --> 00:01:03,600
This strategy involves finding trending days based 
on the central pivot range, a leading indicator,  

14
00:01:03,600 --> 00:01:07,520
and taking trades around safe areas, 
in the direction of the main trend,  

15
00:01:07,520 --> 00:01:10,640
using simple price action.
By the end of this video,  

16
00:01:10,640 --> 00:01:15,040
you’ll know right at the beginning of the 
day if you are going to trade your market  

17
00:01:15,040 --> 00:01:17,280
and you’ll also know the 
direction you’ll follow. 
  

18
00:01:18,560 --> 00:01:22,720
If I have to name my favorite 
indicator, well it’s the Pivot Points. 

19
00:01:22,720 --> 00:01:28,160
Pivots are nothing but support/resistance, 
based on the high/low/close of previous day  

20
00:01:28,160 --> 00:01:32,880
and offers you a framework to trade on.
By plotting Pivot Points on your chart,  

21
00:01:32,880 --> 00:01:36,960
it will show you boundaries, where price 
is likely to face support/resistance. 

22
00:01:37,520 --> 00:01:42,240
Unlike lagging indicators, pivots don’t 
change as you change your timeframe,  

23
00:01:42,240 --> 00:01:47,120
once you plot them on your chart at the market 
opening, they remain there until market closes. 

24
00:01:47,840 --> 00:01:51,360
And one more aspect, pivots 
are being used by big players.
  

25
00:01:52,720 --> 00:01:56,480
I came to know about the Central 
Pivot Range concept after reading  

26
00:01:56,480 --> 00:02:02,960
the “The Logical Trader” by Mark Fischer.
CPR is nothing but a range of 3 lines, one above  

27
00:02:02,960 --> 00:02:08,640
and one below the central pivot point of the day.
The fundamental idea behind this indicator is that  

28
00:02:08,640 --> 00:02:13,040
the particular day’s trading range captures 
everything about the market sentiment,  

29
00:02:13,600 --> 00:02:17,440
so this range can be used to predict the 
price movement of the following days.
  

30
00:02:18,880 --> 00:02:21,840
How to read the price action 
using the Central Pivot Range. 

31
00:02:22,480 --> 00:02:27,360
When the CPR makes higher highs, meaning 
CPR is higher than the previous day,  

32
00:02:27,360 --> 00:02:30,000
that indicates that the particular 
market is in an uptrend. 

33
00:02:30,640 --> 00:02:35,680
When the CPR makes lower lows, meaning 
CPR is lower compared to the previous day,  

34
00:02:35,680 --> 00:02:41,680
this indicates that the market is in a downtrend.
As long as the price is above CPR, it is generally  

35
00:02:41,680 --> 00:02:47,440
known as bullish day, and as long as the price 
is trading below CPR, we are in a bearish day 

36
00:02:48,240 --> 00:02:54,160
Of course, this doesn’t mean if you see price 
trading above CPR you’ll go and buy it. CPR is  

37
00:02:54,160 --> 00:02:58,480
just a guideline, and I will show you later 
how to filter and find the best signals.
  

38
00:02:59,920 --> 00:03:04,320
The wider the Central Pivot Range, the more 
difficult for the price to break the area. 

39
00:03:04,880 --> 00:03:10,640
This basically means that wider Central Pivot 
Ranges are more powerful than a narrow width CPR. 

40
00:03:11,360 --> 00:03:17,200
Have a look at this chart. This was a wide 
CPR day, and when price retraced to the area,  

41
00:03:17,200 --> 00:03:23,680
it found support and was unable to go below it.
And look what happened when the CPR was narrow.  

42
00:03:23,680 --> 00:03:27,440
The price broke on both sides of 
the area, hunting stop orders.  

43
00:03:28,080 --> 00:03:33,360
And no clear trend during the day, just sideways 
price movement and lots of consolidation. 

44
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:40,240
So if CPR is too narrow it's unlikely the CPR 
will offer a solid support or resistance area. 

45
00:03:40,880 --> 00:03:46,080
Whenever CPR is too narrow I don’t pay 
much importance if the price comes near it,  

46
00:03:46,080 --> 00:03:48,240
because it can easily pierce it and break it. 

47
00:03:48,800 --> 00:03:53,360
So, remember, narrow CPR doesn’t 
offer much support/resistance.
 
 
 
 
 

48
00:03:54,800 --> 00:03:59,040
Also, when Central Pivot Range 
is wider, often but not always,  

49
00:03:59,040 --> 00:04:04,240
such days are range days, where price moves 
from one range to another throughout the day. 

50
00:04:05,040 --> 00:04:10,800
Look at this example. We had a strong move 
upward, so the next day the CPR was quite wide. 

51
00:04:11,360 --> 00:04:15,440
We had a range day, around this 
area. And remember the previous rule.  

52
00:04:15,440 --> 00:04:19,680
A wide range means that it’s more difficult 
for the price to break the area. 
 
  

53
00:04:20,960 --> 00:04:25,200
Another observation is that a narrow 
Central Pivot Range can lead to a big  

54
00:04:25,200 --> 00:04:30,240
trending day and wide Central Pivot Range 
can lead to quiet and range bound day. 

55
00:04:31,120 --> 00:04:36,400
In this example, you can see a very narrow 
range day, which lead to a huge move during  

56
00:04:36,400 --> 00:04:42,240
the day. Observe how the price was trending 
in one direction, with lots of momentum. 

57
00:04:42,240 --> 00:04:46,400
And of course, after such a strong 
trending day, the next day was a wide  

58
00:04:46,400 --> 00:04:52,000
range CPR, with sideways price action.
This an efficient way to analyze price,  

59
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:55,000
quite different from the classic 
price action techniques. 
  

60
00:04:55,840 --> 00:05:00,240
There’s another high probability setup, 
and that is the Fresh Central Pivot Range. 

61
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:05,440
If on any given day, price didn’t 
touch its CPR, it will be considered  

62
00:05:05,440 --> 00:05:11,440
as Fresh CPR for next coming 2 or 3 days.
Here’s an example, the price made an aggressive  

63
00:05:11,440 --> 00:05:18,080
move downward and the next day, price action 
didn’t touch its CPR. So that was a Fresh CPR,  

64
00:05:18,080 --> 00:05:21,120
an important area to keep an eye 
on for the next several days.
 
  

65
00:05:22,480 --> 00:05:27,120
Sometimes, during the trading day, you’ll 
see no candlesticks inside the CPR,  

66
00:05:27,120 --> 00:05:30,560
but only one or two wicks entering inside the CPR.  

67
00:05:30,560 --> 00:05:35,200
This is also a Fresh CPR and still a 
very powerful support/resistance area. 

68
00:05:35,920 --> 00:05:39,200
And here an interesting fact I 
found out after my backtesting. 

69
00:05:39,760 --> 00:05:45,680
Price respects a Fresh CPR at the opening of 
the session compared to mid to late afternoon. 

70
00:05:46,400 --> 00:05:52,640
So if the previous day was a fresh CPR, and 
today at the opening, price approaches the area,  

71
00:05:52,640 --> 00:05:56,960
then that fresh CPR has a high chance to 
work as a strong support or resistance. 

72
00:05:57,680 --> 00:06:02,960
If price approaches the previous day fresh 
CPR after the middle of the trading session,  

73
00:06:02,960 --> 00:06:08,480
then the CPR isn’t likely to work as strong 
support/resistance and price can easily break it.
  

74
00:06:09,760 --> 00:06:13,120
Here’s an example.
We have a Fresh CPR on chart,  

75
00:06:13,120 --> 00:06:18,720
and on the next day, the market opened below 
the fresh CPR, touched it, and the area acted  

76
00:06:18,720 --> 00:06:26,000
as resistance and price immediately reversed.
So Fresh CPR works as strong support/resistance  

77
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:30,000
at opening and less powerful during 
the second part of the trading day.
  

78
00:06:31,280 --> 00:06:36,640
Plotting the CPR on your chart can give you 
a great edge in your Trading. CPR is also  

79
00:06:36,640 --> 00:06:41,920
known as “heartbeat” of the market where price is 
likely to change its direction most of the time. 

80
00:06:41,920 --> 00:06:46,720
CPR is a powerful support and resistance 
area. So, it is not a good idea to go short  

81
00:06:46,720 --> 00:06:51,760
when price is above the CPR, because it 
will act as a support area, and it’s not a  

82
00:06:51,760 --> 00:06:56,720
good idea to go long when price is below CPR 
because it will act as a resistance area.
  

83
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:03,600
The idea of the strategy is to buy and sell the 
waves of a trend. One of the best ways to buy  

84
00:07:03,600 --> 00:07:08,400
and sell pullbacks in a trend is to play 
the bounces off the central pivot range,  

85
00:07:08,400 --> 00:07:14,400
which is the method many professionals use.
Essentially, each pull-back to the pivot range  

86
00:07:14,400 --> 00:07:18,960
is a buying opportunity within an uptrend, 
and a selling opportunity in a downtrend. 

87
00:07:19,600 --> 00:07:23,600
How do I define a trend, 
using the CPR? Very simple. 

88
00:07:23,600 --> 00:07:29,280
If the current day CPR is higher than the 
previous one, we have a short term uptrend.  

89
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:34,720
We look for long entries above the CPR.
If the current day CPR is lower than the  

90
00:07:34,720 --> 00:07:41,440
previous one, we have a short term downtrend. We 
look for short entries below the CPR. This is an  

91
00:07:41,440 --> 00:07:46,400
important condition in our strategy.
 
So at the beginning of the day,  

92
00:07:46,400 --> 00:07:51,680
the first step you need to take is to analyze the 
position of the CPR, relative to the previous day. 

93
00:07:51,680 --> 00:07:56,400
• If it’s higher, you know that during the 
day you’ll be searching for long entries. 

94
00:07:56,400 --> 00:07:59,600
• If it’s lower, you know 
you want to short the market. 

95
00:08:00,320 --> 00:08:06,080
If the CPR is wide, you know that the price will 
most likely find support or resistance at the CPR,  

96
00:08:06,640 --> 00:08:09,360
but you will also be prepared 
for ranging conditions. 

97
00:08:10,320 --> 00:08:15,200
If the CPR is narrow, you can have a 
strong trending day, but at the same time,  

98
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:21,600
the CPR may not offer much support and resistance.
Using the H1 time frame, you remove the noise on  

99
00:08:21,600 --> 00:08:26,320
the lower time frames. Just by looking at the 
chart at the beginning of the trading day,  

100
00:08:26,320 --> 00:08:31,120
you’ll know what to expect. This is how 
trading should be. Planned and organized.
 
  

101
00:08:32,400 --> 00:08:35,360
Here are several techniques 
I use to filter signals  

102
00:08:35,360 --> 00:08:40,560
and to trade only the high probability ones.
The first one is the classic trend line breakout,  

103
00:08:40,560 --> 00:08:43,760
which is one of the most effective 
strategies if traded correctly. 

104
00:08:44,720 --> 00:08:49,120
Trendlines connect consecutive higher 
lows in an uptrend and consecutive  

105
00:08:49,120 --> 00:08:54,640
lower highs in a downtrend. The idea is to 
use the momentum of a trend line breakout,  

106
00:08:54,640 --> 00:09:00,560
to find areas around CPR area. 
 
 
The strategy here is very simple: 

107
00:09:00,560 --> 00:09:06,080
If the price breaks a downward trendline, the 
CPR is higher compared to the previous day,  

108
00:09:06,080 --> 00:09:11,520
and the price is testing the central pivot 
range from the upper side and founds support,  

109
00:09:11,520 --> 00:09:16,640
then you should look for long positions.
Conversely, if the price breaks an upward  

110
00:09:16,640 --> 00:09:22,000
trendline, the CPR is lower compared to the 
previous day, and the price is testing the  

111
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:27,760
central pivot range from the lower side and founds 
resistance, then you look for short positions.
 
  

112
00:09:29,200 --> 00:09:36,080
Here’s the euro yen. We had a sustained downtrend, 
a 3 days uptrend and a trend line breakout.  

113
00:09:36,080 --> 00:09:41,840
As the price broke this previous swing, it found 
resistance at the lower central pivot range. 

114
00:09:41,840 --> 00:09:46,400
The rejection came in the form of a 
pin bar. As the central pivot range  

115
00:09:46,400 --> 00:09:50,960
was also lower than the previous one, the 
conditions were met for a short position. 

116
00:09:51,680 --> 00:09:58,240
Also, this is a wide range CPR, and we already had 
some previous price action returning to the zone.  

117
00:09:58,800 --> 00:10:05,120
We know that during wide CPRs, we could witness 
some ranges. So a short right below the CPR  

118
00:10:05,120 --> 00:10:09,120
was also in line with this, because the 
price already moved throughout the day. 

119
00:10:09,840 --> 00:10:15,840
Stop loss goes above the CPR or above the 
central pivot point (being a wide range),  

120
00:10:15,840 --> 00:10:22,160
and you target the next big swing or a minimum 
1.5 reward, compared to your risk.
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
  

121
00:10:23,280 --> 00:10:29,680
We have an uptrend, with a 4 day downtrend 
correction, 4 consecutive CPR days. Here we  

122
00:10:29,680 --> 00:10:34,480
have the first up central pivot range, 
and a double bottom around this level. 

123
00:10:35,040 --> 00:10:39,840
The next day was also an up CPR day, with 
the price breaking above this trendline. 

124
00:10:40,400 --> 00:10:44,240
This time, the price managed to 
reach the middle level of the range,  

125
00:10:44,240 --> 00:10:48,560
the central pivot point, found 
support and continued its uptrend. 

126
00:10:49,440 --> 00:10:53,120
Always look for candlestick 
formations to reveal rejection. 

127
00:10:53,120 --> 00:10:56,800
In this case, it was a pin 
bar, forming inside the CPR. 

128
00:10:57,520 --> 00:11:03,200
We also had confluence with this swing high 
breakout, which became support. Long above the  

129
00:11:03,200 --> 00:11:08,880
CPR, with a stop loss either below the pin bar 
inside the CPR, or below the middle CPR line,  

130
00:11:08,880 --> 00:11:13,840
and you target the next swing 
high, right here. 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 
 

131
00:11:57,840 --> 00:12:01,520
The second strategy involves 
the Ichimoku cloud, but we’ll  

132
00:12:01,520 --> 00:12:07,040
use only the conversion line or Tenkan Sen.
The Conversion Line will help you with the  

133
00:12:07,040 --> 00:12:12,000
short-term price momentum and also signals 
an area of minor support or resistance. 

134
00:12:12,000 --> 00:12:18,480
• If the market price is above the conversion 
line, this indicates a short-term upward momentum,  

135
00:12:18,480 --> 00:12:20,960
and you would want to 
concentrate on buying signals 

136
00:12:20,960 --> 00:12:26,960
• If the price is below conversion line, 
this reveals a short-term downward momentum,  

137
00:12:26,960 --> 00:12:32,080
and you would want to search for selling signals
 
 
You also need to pay attention  

138
00:12:32,080 --> 00:12:35,680
to the slope of the line.
• An increasing conversion line,  

139
00:12:35,680 --> 00:12:41,760
meaning an upward slope, indicates an upward trend
• A decreasing conversion line, meaning a downward  

140
00:12:41,760 --> 00:12:46,800
slope, indicates a downward trend
The idea is to find zones with the  

141
00:12:46,800 --> 00:12:51,840
central pivot range and the conversion 
line close together, areas of confluence. 

142
00:12:52,480 --> 00:12:57,920
So if CPR is higher compared to the previous 
day, the price is testing the central pivot  

143
00:12:57,920 --> 00:13:03,440
range from the upper side and stays above the 
conversion line, you look for long entries. 

144
00:13:04,400 --> 00:13:09,520
If CPR is lower compared to the previous 
day, the price is testing the central pivot  

145
00:13:09,520 --> 00:13:14,800
range from the lower side and stays below the 
conversion line, you look for short entries.
 
  

146
00:13:16,080 --> 00:13:20,240
Here’s a long entry. We have an 
upward CPR day, higher than the  

147
00:13:20,240 --> 00:13:26,480
previous day, so we look for long trades.
The CPR is wide, so we expect strong support. 

148
00:13:27,040 --> 00:13:31,120
We also have the conversion line 
offering support. And look what happened  

149
00:13:31,120 --> 00:13:36,880
when price entered the zone. It touched the 
conversion line, formed a pin bar and reversed. 

150
00:13:37,680 --> 00:13:42,640
This strategy offers a lower stop loss. You 
could place it below the conversion line,  

151
00:13:42,640 --> 00:13:48,240
or below the pin bar rejecting the area. You don’t 
need to place it all the way below the area. 
  

152
00:13:49,600 --> 00:13:54,320
And here’s a short Tesla trade.
We found a lower CPR day, price is  

153
00:13:54,320 --> 00:14:00,560
below the conversion line, so downward momentum.
At the opening of the session, price entered the  

154
00:14:00,560 --> 00:14:06,160
central pivot range, and touched to the pip, 
both the upper level and the conversion line,  

155
00:14:06,160 --> 00:14:10,320
and immediately moved in the opposite 
direction, forming yet another pin bar. 

156
00:14:11,040 --> 00:14:14,320
The pin bars are my go-to signals, 
perfect for this strategy. 

157
00:14:14,960 --> 00:14:19,440
As there is clearly bearish pressure, we 
took a short trade right after the pin bar. 

158
00:14:20,080 --> 00:14:24,560
Stop loss above the conversion line, 
which is also above the pin bar and CPR,  

159
00:14:25,120 --> 00:14:29,120
targeting the next swing.
If and when price moves above  

160
00:14:29,120 --> 00:14:33,920
the conversion line, you need to be careful 
and close at least a part of your position  

161
00:14:33,920 --> 00:14:43,840
because momentum is shifting 
to the other side.
 
 
 
 
 
  

